# Functional Programming

Prefer a functional approach over imperative programming. Favor immutable data, pure functions, and declarative transforms.

## Immutability

- Use `const` when the binding does not need reassignment
- Avoid reassigning variables (`x = ...` multiple times)
- Do not mutate arrays (`push`, `pop`, `splice`, in-place `sort`, in-place `reverse`)
- Do not mutate objects (`obj.prop = ...`, `delete obj.prop`)
- Do not modify props or data received as arguments

- ✅ Good:

  ```typescript
  const activeUsers = users.filter((user) => user.isActive)
  const sortedNames = [...names].sort((a, b) => a.localeCompare(b))
  const updatedUser = { ...user, name: 'Jane' }
  ```

- ❌ Bad:

  ```typescript
  let result = []
  for (const user of users) {
    if (user.isActive) result.push(user)
  }

  names.sort()
  user.name = 'Jane'
  ```

## Data Transforms

- Prefer `map`, `filter`, `reduce`, `find`, `some`, and `every` over `for` and `forEach` when producing new values
- Avoid building arrays manually (`const arr = []; arr.push(...)`)
- Avoid conditionals that mutate intermediate state (`if (...) result = ...`)
- Prefer expressions over long sequences of statements when readability improves

- ✅ Good:

  ```typescript
  const projectSlugs = projects
    .filter((project) => project.isPublished)
    .map((project) => project.slug)

  const hasActiveProject = projects.some((project) => project.isActive)
  ```

- ❌ Bad:

  ```typescript
  const projectSlugs = []
  for (const project of projects) {
    if (project.isPublished) {
      projectSlugs.push(project.slug)
    }
  }

  let hasActiveProject = false
  projects.forEach((project) => {
    if (project.isActive) hasActiveProject = true
  })
  ```

## Purity and Composition

- Keep functions pure whenever possible — same input, same output, no side effects
- Avoid shared mutable variables between functions
- Prefer function composition over long sequential logic
- Derive values from state instead of manually syncing them

- ✅ Good:

  ```typescript
  const getFullName = (user: User) => `${user.firstName} ${user.lastName}`

  const getDisplayName = (user: User | null) => {
    if (!user) return null
    return getFullName(user)
  }

  const fullName = getFullName(user)
  ```

- ❌ Bad:

  ```typescript
  let cachedName = ''

  const updateName = (user: User) => {
    cachedName = `${user.firstName} ${user.lastName}`
  }

  const getDisplayName = () => cachedName
  ```

## React

- Avoid side effects inside render
- Do not manually sync derived values — compute them from state or props
- Avoid direct DOM manipulation when a React solution exists; use `useRef` only when necessary

- ✅ Good:

  ```typescript
  const visibleProjects = projects.filter((project) => project.isVisible)

  return (
    <ul>
      {visibleProjects.map((project) => (
        <li key={project.id}>{project.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  )
  ```

- ❌ Bad:

  ```typescript
  const items = []
  for (const project of projects) {
    if (project.isVisible) items.push(<li key={project.id}>{project.name}</li>)
  }

  document.getElementById('list')?.appendChild(node)

  return <ul>{items}</ul>
  ```
